<dl id="n38038c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n38" href="#n38038c">N38 (VI.B.32)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n38all.htm#n38038c"> 38(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> the case is altered / inn</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><b>Letters to the Editor</b> <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> &ldquo;The Case is Altered&rdquo; / Origin of a Mysterious Inn Sign <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> Sir.&mdash;In the main road through Banbury to Exford <mark>stands an inn with the sign &ldquo;The Case is Altered.&rdquo;</mark> What is its origin and significance? / (Dr.) G.E. Weeks / Fenny Compton Rectory, / Leamington. / <font color="green">[The Inn near Banbury referred to in the letter above was so called on account of its being built &ldquo;on the site of a mere hovel,&rdquo; according to Larwood, who adds, &ldquo;&lsquo;The Case is Altered&rsquo; generally alludes to some alteration in the affairs of the landlord.&rdquo; This sign was adopted at Oxford by the new landlord of an Inn to show that the easy-going ways of his predecessor in the matter of giving credit had been abandoned.&mdash;Editor, &ldquo;M.P.&rdquo;]</font> <small> <a name="MP24may30" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#MP24may30"><cite title="source">Morning Post</cite></a> (24 May 1930) 6-4</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
